dispose() {\n       _socketClient?.disconnect();\n       super.dispose();\n     
}\n     ```\n     If the user logs out, the HomePage might be disposed (if navig
ating to login), so `_socketClient` is disconnected and set to null? Actually `d
isconnect()` sets `_socket = null` but doesn\'t set the outer `_socketClient` to
null. Wait:\n     ```dart\n     void disconnect() {\n       _socket?.disconnect(
);\n       _socket = null;\n     }\n     ```\n     This doesn\'t set `MatchingSo
cketClient` instance to null in `HomePage`. So if the page is not disposed (e.g.
, auth state changes but page stays mounted), `_socketClient` remains non-null a
nd `_initSocket()` returns early. If the page IS disposed, `_socketClient` is lo
st anyway. But when logging back in, a new HomePage is created, so `_socketClien
t` starts as null.\n\n     However, there\'s another scenario: token refresh. If
