    think='Good - the migration exists and includes all the matching-related tab
les. So database migration is covered.\n\nNow let me compile the review findings
. Let me organize them:\n\n**Blocking Issues:**\n1. Mobile uses handwritten mode
ls instead of OpenAPI generated models - violates flutter.md "所有 Model 使用 fr
eezed + json_serializable" and duplicates generated code. The generated models e
xist but are unused.\n\n**Major Issues:**\n1. **MatchingGateway hardcodes jwtCon
fig import** - should use ConfigService per NestJS config best practices and nes
tjs.md doesn\'t explicitly forbid this but it\'s an architecture concern. Actual
ly, looking at nestjs.md, it says "配置加载（@nestjs/config）" in the project st
ructure. The hardcoded import bypasses the configuration system. I\'ll classify 
this as Major.\n   \n2. **Swipe action UI rollback on failure**: In `MatchingBlo
c`, when a swipe API fails, the card is already removed from the UI (state = `Ma
tchingSwipeInProgress` with card removed) and then it emits `MatchingFailure`. T
he user can\'t retry the swipe on the same card because it\'s gone. This breaks 
data consistency between UI and backend. Major UX issue.\n\n3. **MatchingSocketC
lient lacks error handling**: No connection error handling, no retry, no reconne
ction logic. If the socket disconnects, the user won\'t receive match notificati
ons. Major for real-time feature.\n\n4. **BDD step definitions test the wrong ab
straction**: The BDD tests for mutual like mock `matchRepo.findOne` at the repos
itory level, but the actual code uses `manager.findOne` inside a transaction. Th
e tests don\'t properly verify transaction behavior. This is a test quality issu
e.\n\n**Minor Issues:**\n1. `MatchingService.onModuleDestroy` quits Redis, but `
MatchingModule` creates a new Redis instance per module. If the module is destro
yed and recreated, a new Redis connection is made. This is okay but could be opt
imized with a shared Redis provider.\n2. `HomePage._submitSwipe` uses `Future.de
layed(200ms)` for animation before calling bloc - if user navigates away during 
this delay, the bloc event might be added to a disposed bloc. Minor.\n3. `SwipeA
ctionDto` doesn\'t have `@IsUUID()` for `target_id`. Minor.\n4. `MatchListPage` 
uses `Icons.chat_bubble_outline` for empty state - this is a Material icon, whic
h is allowed since it\'s not a button/input.\n5. `docs/api/socket-events.md` use
s markdown instead of YAML as recommended by `api.md` ("契约文档：docs/api-contr
acts/<module>-events.yaml"). Not a big issue.\n6. `widgetbook/main.dart` has `_S
erverUrlToolDemo` using `onChanged` on `SwTextField` - according to flutter.md, 
`TextField.onChanged` is problematic for Maestro. But this is a Widgetbook demo,
not production code.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider the Blocking issue about hand
written models. Let me re-read flutter.md carefully:\n> 所有 Model 使用 freezed 
+ json_serializable\n> OpenAPI 生成模型存放在 apps/mobile/lib/models/generated/<
module>/，禁止手动修改生成文件\n\nThe PR adds both generated models AND handwrit
ten models. The handwritten models don\'t use freezed. They also define their ow
n `fromJson`/`toJson`/`==`/`hashCode` instead of using the generated ones. This 
is definitely a violation of the coding standard.\n\nBut is it Blocking? The cod
e works functionally, but it violates architectural standards and creates mainte
nance overhead (two sources of truth for the same schema). According to the revi
ew framework, "Blocking" is for "功能不可用、数据丢失、安全漏洞". This is more o
f a "Major" issue because it affects maintainability but doesn\'t break function
ality.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The `packages/shared-types` is supposed t
o be "前后端的唯一真实来源" per AGENTS.md. And the mobile app has generated Dart
models from the OpenAPI spec. Using handwritten models means:\n- If the API cont
ract changes, the generated models are updated but the handwritten ones might no
t be\n- The `shared-types` package is not the single source of truth for the mob
ile app\n\nThis is a significant architecture violation. I\'ll mark it as **Majo
r** since it\'s not making the feature completely unusable, but it\'s a serious 
maintainability risk.\n\nLet me think about whether there are any Blocking issue
s...\n\nActually, I need to look more carefully at the `MatchingBloc` state mach
ine. When a swipe action is submitted:\n\n```dart\nfinal updatedCards = currentS
tate.cards.where((c) => c.userId != event.targetId).toList();\nemit(MatchingSwip
eInProgress(cards: updatedCards, ...));\ntry {\n  final result = await _matching
Repository.recordSwipeAction(...);\n  ...\n} on Exception catch (_) {\n  emit(co
nst MatchingFailure(\'网络异常，请检查连接后重试\'));\n}\n```\n\nIf the API call
fails, the state becomes `MatchingFailure`. The user sees an error. But the card
is gone from the list. The user would have to pull-to-refresh or re-enter the pa
ge to get the card back. This is bad UX but the feature still works. Not Blockin
g.\n\nWhat about the `HomePage` socket? If `_initSocket` is called before auth s
tate is authenticated, it returns early. The `BlocListener` on AuthBloc will tri
gger when auth becomes authenticated. But what if auth is ALREADY authenticated 
when HomePage is built? Then `initState` calls `_initSocket`, `authState is Auth
Authenticated` is true, socket connects. Good.\n\nWhat if the token expires whil
e the socket is connected? The gateway will disconnect the socket. But the mobil
e client has no reconnection logic. This means match notifications will be lost 
until the user re-enters the home page. This is a functional gap for real-time n
otifications. I\'ll classify this as **Major**.\n\nLet me also check the `matchi
ng.service.ts` for a potential race condition in `checkAndCreateMutualMatch`:\n\
n```typescript\nconst mutual = await this.matchActionRepo.findOne({\n  where: {\
n    actor_id: targetId,\n    target_id: actorId,\n    action: "like",\n  },\n})
;\n\nif (!mutual) {\n  return { isMatch: false };\n}\n\nreturn this.dataSource.t
ransaction(async (manager) => {\n  ...\n});\n```\n\nThe mutual like check is OUT
SIDE the transaction. This means:\n1. Alice likes Bob -> match_actions record cr
eated\n2. Bob checks for mutual like -> finds Alice\'s like\n3. Bob starts trans
action to create match\n4. Alice unlikes Bob (if that were possible) or some oth
er operation\n5. Bob\'s transaction completes\n\nActually, unliking is not imple
mented. So this race condition is limited. But there is still a potential race w
here two users simultaneously like each other and both try to create a match. Th
e unique index on `(user_a_id, user_b_id)` handles this, and the catch block ret
urns the existing match. So this is actually handled correctly.\n\nHowever, ther
e is a subtle issue: between the `matchActionRepo.findOne` (checking for mutual 
like) and the `dataSource.transaction`, another process could also see the mutua
l like and try to create the same match. Both would enter the transaction, one w
ould succeed, the other would hit the unique constraint and fall back to finding
the existing match. This is handled. Good.\n\nWait, I found another potential is
sue. In `matching.service.ts`:\n\n```typescript\nasync getRecommendations(...): 
Promise<RecommendationResponseDto[]> {\n  ...\n  const cached = await this.redis
.get(cacheKey);\n  if (cached) {\n    try {\n      const parsed = JSON.parse(cac
hed) as CachedRecommendation[];\n      const userIds = parsed.map((p) => p.user_
id);\n      return this.buildRecommendations(userIds, userId);\n    } catch {\n 
    // Cache corruption, fall through\n    }\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nWhen cache h
it, it calls `buildRecommendations(userIds, userId)`. This method queries `profi
leRepo.findBy({ user_id: In(userIds) })` and `profileRepo.findOne({ where: { use
r_id: currentUserId } })` for distance calculation. But it doesn\'t check if the
user profiles are still `is_complete = true` or if blocks have been added since 
caching. The PRD says:\n> 拉黑操作时主动清除双方 Redis 推荐缓存\n\nBut if a bloc
k is created and the cache is not cleared (e.g., by a bug in the blocks module),
the cached recommendations could include blocked users. The blocks module (`Bloc
ksService.create`) doesn\'t clear Redis cache! This is a functional gap.\n\nLook
ing at `BlocksService.create`:\n```typescript\nasync create(dto: CreateBlockDto)
: Promise<void> {\n  const existing = await this.blockRepo.findOne({...});\n  if
(existing) { return; }\n  const block = this.blockRepo.create({...});\n  await t
his.blockRepo.save(block);\n}\n```\n\nIt doesn\'t clear any Redis cache. The PRD
says:\n> 拉黑操作时主动清除双方 Redis 推荐缓存\n\nAnd in the risk table:\n> 缓存
与数据库状态不一致（用户被拉黑后仍出现在推荐中） | 中 | 拉黑操作时主动清除双方 R
edis 推荐缓存\n\nThis is a **Major** issue because the blocks module doesn\'t fu
lfill the contract with the matching module. However, the blocks module might no
t be in the scope of this PR. The PR touches `blocks.service.ts` but I should ch
eck what the actual change is. Looking at `.doc-coverage.txt`, `apps/api/src/mod
ules/blocks/blocks.service.ts` is listed as a changed file. But I read it and it
seems like a basic implementation. Let me check if this file was newly added or 
modified.\n\nActually, looking at the `.doc-coverage.txt`, it lists all changed 
files. The blocks module might have existed before. The PR doesn\'t seem to have
modified it significantly. But since the PR includes matching functionality that
depends on blocks, and the blocks module doesn\'t clear cache, this is a cross-m
odule integration issue.\n\nWait, I should check if the blocks service was actua
lly changed in this PR or if it was pre-existing. Let me check git diff info. Bu
t I don\'t have direct access to the git diff. The `.doc-coverage.txt` just list
s changed files. Let me check if `blocks.service.ts` is in the diff by looking a
